problem:
Evaluate \begin{align*}
\left(c^c-c(c-1)^c\right)^c
\end{align*} when $c=3$.

solution:
We rewrite $\left(\sqrt[4]{11}\right)^{6x+2}$ and then substitute the given equation: \begin{align*}
\left(\sqrt[4]{11}\right)^{6x+2}&=\left(\sqrt[4]{11}\right)^{6x-6}\cdot \left(\sqrt[4]{11}\right)^{8}\\
&=\left(\left(\sqrt[4]{11}\right)^{3x-3}\right)^2\cdot\left(11^{1/4}\right)^{8}\\
&=\left(\frac{1}{5}\right)^2\cdot11^{(8/4)}\\
&=\frac{1}{25}\cdot121\\
&=\boxed{\frac{121}{25}}
\end{align*}

We may carry out long division in base 4 just as in base 10. We have  \[
\begin{array}{cc|cccc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & 3 & 3 \\
\cline{3-6}
1 & 1 & 1 & 0 & 2 & 3 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} && 3&3& \downarrow \\ \cline{4-5}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} && 0&3&3 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & 3&3 \\ \cline{5-6}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & & 0 \\
\end{array}
\]for a quotient of $\boxed{33_4}$. Note that in the above calculation we have used that $11_4\cdot3_4=5_{10}\cdot3_{10}=15_{10}=33_4$. Then, for the second step we used $33_4$ divided by $11_4$ is $3_4$.

